They have checked the system resources and usage but require assistance in resolving the issue. They have requested that this issue be escalated to the Hardware Support Team for further investigation.
close_notes: The issue was caused by excessive background processes consuming system resources. Initial troubleshooting steps included: 1) Checking Task Manager for high CPU/RAM usage. Found several non-essential applications running. 2) Disabled startup programs using 'msconfig'. 3) Updated all software and drivers to the latest versions. 4) Ran a full system scan for malware using the company's antivirus software. 5) Cleaned up temporary files using 'Disk Cleanup'. The computer's performance improved significantly after these steps. The ticket does not need escalation to the Hardware Support Team as the issue was resolved.
output: Software/System: Computer ; Issue/Request: Slow computer performance

Updated the TNSNAMES.ORA file with the correct connect identifier and ensured that the Oracle listener was running. 
Tested the connection to confirm that the SCCM application could now resolve the database connection without errors. 
Informed the customer of the changes made and provided guidance on verifying the connection settings in the future. 
The customer confirmed that SCCM is now functioning correctly and the issue has been resolved.

short_description: LogRhythm SIEM Problem
content: Hello, I'm having trouble using the LogRhythm SIEM application. Every time I try to use it, I get an error message saying 'java.security.cert.CertificateException: No subject alternative DNS name matching 'api.example.com' found.' I even tried reinstalling the application, but the same error keeps popping up. Can someone please help me fix this issue?
close_notes:
Investigated the error message 'java.security.cert.CertificateException: No subject alternative DNS name matching 'api.example.com' found' reported by the user. 
Checked the LogRhythm SIEM application configuration and confirmed that the API endpoint was correctly set. 
Identified that the SSL certificate for the API endpoint did not include the necessary Subject Alternative Name (SAN) for 'api.example.com'. 
Recommended the user contact their network administrator to update the SSL certificate to include the correct SAN. 
Informed the user that reinstalling the application would not resolve this certificate issue. 
Provided guidance on how to verify the SSL certificate once it has been updated. 
The user acknowledged the steps and will follow up with their network team. 
Ticket closed as the issue has been clearly identified and the user has a plan for resolution.

short_description: MySQL performance issues during data-intensive operations.
content: I've noticed that MySQL has been really slow, especially when dealing with lots of data. I've checked my hardware, and everything seems fine there, so it doesn't look like the problem is with my equipment.
close_notes: Upon receiving reports regarding MySQL's diminished speed during data-intensive operations, a series of troubleshooting steps were performed. Initially, hardware checks were conducted to rule out any limitations, and these checks were cleared. Subsequently, the focus shifted to the MySQL configuration and query optimization. We identified several poorly optimized queries that were consuming significant resources. These queries were rewritten for better performance. Additionally, we optimized several MySQL configuration parameters such as innodb_buffer_pool_size and query_cache_size to better allocate memory resources and enhance performance. After these adjustments, performance tests were conducted, and it was confirmed that the MySQL server was functioning efficiently under high data loads. The issue has been resolved and normal operations restored.

short_description: Symantec Endpoint Protection causing lag during data analysis operations
content:
Complaints have been lodged about Symantec Endpoint Protection lagging, especially during intensive data analysis operations. We've executed initial diagnostics to dismiss any hardware-related faults. 

This case is now with the Performance Optimization Team for further investigation.
close_notes: Initial diagnosis indicated that hardware was not the root cause of the performance issues with Symantec Endpoint Protection. Conducted a thorough check of system resources and found that the lag coincides with the antivirus deep scans. To resolve the issue, we adjusted the Symantec scan settings by rescheduling the deep scans to off-peak hours and excluding the directories used in the data analysis from real-time scans. Performance significantly improved post-adjustment. User confirmed resolution and system has been performing optimally since.
issue/request: Symantec Endpoint Protection Slow Performance Issue

short_description: Client facing storage issues due to index mismanagement
content: Upon receiving the client's complaint about excessive storage utilization in their Elastic Security deployment, a thorough assessment was conducted. It became evident that the root of the problem lies in the mismanagement of indices—specifically, the indices are neither rolling over nor being deleted as their retention policy intends. This misconfiguration is leading to significant, unnecessary storage consumption. We need to guide the client through checking the index management settings, ensuring proper lifecycle management processes are in place to prevent reaching critical storage levels.
close_notes:
Conducted a thorough assessment of the client's Elastic Security deployment to address excessive storage utilization. 
Identified that the root cause of the issue was the mismanagement of indices, which were neither rolling over nor being deleted according to the established retention policy. 
Guided the client through the process of checking their index management settings to ensure proper lifecycle management is in place. 
Discussed the importance of configuring index rollover and deletion to prevent unnecessary storage consumption. 
Provided recommendations for monitoring index performance and storage levels to avoid reaching critical thresholds in the future. 
The client is now aware of the necessary steps to manage their indices effectively and prevent similar issues moving forward. 
Ticket closed as the issue has been resolved and the client is satisfied with the guidance provided.
issue/request: Index management issues resulting in excessive storage use.
output: Software/System: Elastic Security (Elasticsearch SIEM) ; Issue/Request: Index management issues resulting in excessive storage use.
poor_close_notes: Issue resolved. Client's storage concerns addressed. No further action required.

short_description: Addressing app inconsistencies from time sync issues
content: A customer has reported inconsistencies in their application behavior, likely arising from a time mismatch between cluster and node times in their Kubernetes setup. We need a detailed investigation into the time synchronization process and ensure the time settings across the nodes and cluster are uniformly adjusted to correct and prevent further disruption in tasks and application workflows.
close_notes:
Investigated the reported inconsistencies in application behavior related to time synchronization issues within the Kubernetes setup. 
Checked the time settings on all nodes and the cluster to identify any discrepancies. 
Discovered that there were mismatches in the system time across several nodes, which was causing the application inconsistencies. 
Adjusted the time settings on the affected nodes to ensure they were synchronized with the cluster time. 
Implemented NTP (Network Time Protocol) on all nodes to maintain consistent time across the environment going forward. 
Tested the application behavior post-adjustment and confirmed that the inconsistencies were resolved. 
Provided the customer with documentation on monitoring time synchronization and maintaining uniformity across their Kubernetes setup. 
The customer expressed satisfaction with the resolution and understanding of the changes made.

Logged into the server hosting the MySQL instance and reviewed the MySQL error logs located at /var/log/mysql/error.log. 2. Identified multiple instances of 'InnoDB: Error' messages indicating potential data corruption. 3. Verified MySQL configuration settings in the my.cnf file to ensure optimal settings and no misconfigurations. 4. Ran the MySQL built-in diagnostic tool 'mysqlcheck' to detect and repair corrupt tables. Command used: mysqlcheck -u root -p --auto-repair --check --all-databases 5. Restarted the MySQL service using the systemctl restart mysql command. 6. Tested by saving data into the database, and confirmed there were no crashes. Outcome: Issue resolved by repairing corrupt tables and verifying MySQL configuration settings.
